1
00:00:00,880 --> 00:00:03,760
Germany will soon crash into the consequences of a

2
00:00:03,760 --> 00:00:08,720
fertility crisis made much worse by the\h
mismanagement of the boomer generation.

3
00:00:08,720 --> 00:00:12,640
The demographic collapse tearing up\h
the generational contract may soon

4
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:16,960
destroy one of Germany's greatest\h
achievements: Its welfare state.

5
00:00:16,960 --> 00:00:21,520
Millennials, GenZ and younger are left\h
with a huge mess they somehow need to sort,

6
00:00:21,520 --> 00:00:25,328
while they’re outvoted by the grey\h
block making the decisions for them.

7
00:00:25,328 --> 00:00:26,057
What happened?

8
00:00:33,120 --> 00:00:34,493
Population Collapse

9
00:00:35,280 --> 00:00:39,200
Germany was among the first countries\h
to industrialize and so its fertility

10
00:00:39,200 --> 00:00:42,080
rates dropped early in the 20th century.

11
00:00:42,080 --> 00:00:49,280
But for 55 years, they have\hbeen below
replacement, at 1.4 children per woman in 2025.

12
00:00:49,280 --> 00:00:54,400
Compared to South Korea this sounds almost\h
amazing but it still means population collapse.

13
00:00:54,400 --> 00:00:59,200
If fertility stays at 1.4 then 100 Germans will have 70kids.

14
00:00:59,200 --> 00:01:04,960
When those grow up, they will have 49 kids,\h
who will then have 34 kids, who will have 24.

15
00:01:04,960 --> 00:01:08,400
A 76% drop within four generations.

16
00:01:08,400 --> 00:01:12,320
Many people think there are too many\h
humans anyways, so what is the big deal?

17
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:15,920
Well at the same time people\h
started living much, much longer.

18
00:01:15,920 --> 00:01:20,960
So we have a fatal mix of way more\h
grannies and way fewer babies.

19
00:01:20,960 --> 00:01:24,800
The real crisis German Millennials,\h
Gen-Z and younger will have to live

20
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:29,680
through is the massive shift in population\h
composition and the transition period.

21
00:01:29,680 --> 00:01:32,960
In 2026 Germany is already\h
one of the oldest countries

22
00:01:32,960 --> 00:01:36,640
in the world with a median age of over 45.

23
00:01:36,640 --> 00:01:42,400
Almost two in five Germans are over 50,\h
almost one in four is older than 65.

24
00:01:42,400 --> 00:01:45,360
Only one in 8 is a child under 14.

25
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:50,080
Despite its industrial production declining,\h
suffocating bureaucracy and little economic

26
00:01:50,080 --> 00:01:55,520
growth, Germany's system is still chugging along\h
and it remains one of the richest countries.

27
00:01:55,520 --> 00:01:58,720
The country still has a big\h
population and a big workforce,

28
00:01:58,720 --> 00:02:02,000
along with generous social\h
benefits and pension payouts.

29
00:02:02,000 --> 00:02:04,720
But soon the reality of demographics and

30
00:02:04,720 --> 00:02:08,720
boomer mismanagement will hit\h
Germany like a freight train.

31
00:02:08,720 --> 00:02:14,000
Population crash means that a society\h
and culture loses more than just people.

32
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:19,069
The systems and countries we have built can’t\h
just be downscaled, things stop working.

33
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:21,760
Young Germans Are Screwed.

34
00:02:21,760 --> 00:02:22,750
Old Ones too.

35
00:02:23,424 --> 00:02:30,000
By 2036, 13 million German Baby boomers\h
will retire – this big bulge here.

36
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,607
But because they didn’t have nearly enough kids\h
way fewer younger people will replace them

37
00:02:34,607 --> 00:02:39,280
– in 2030 alone there might be millions 
of\hjobs that will be impossible to fill.

38
00:02:39,280 --> 00:02:43,840
Fewer people working means fewer\h
taxes and resources for the state.

39
00:02:43,840 --> 00:02:46,720
Also services will decline,\h
waiting times will increase

40
00:02:46,720 --> 00:02:50,400
for everything from your bags at the\h
airport to doctor's appointments.

41
00:02:50,400 --> 00:02:53,520
But the much more urgent issue is retirees.

42
00:02:53,520 --> 00:02:55,920
Germany has a “pay as you go” pension system,

43
00:02:55,920 --> 00:03:01,200
which means that about 20% of today’s\h
salaries is directly paid out to pensioners.

44
00:03:01,200 --> 00:03:06,560
This sort of worked in the 1960s when there\h
were five working Germans for every retiree.

45
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:10,800
But in 2024 this ratio is down to about 2.5.

46
00:03:10,800 --> 00:03:14,880
In the 2030s it will get closer\h
to 2 workers for one pensioner.

47
00:03:14,880 --> 00:03:17,520
And about ten years after retirement people tend

48
00:03:17,520 --> 00:03:21,840
to get really sick and cause the\h
vast majority of health care costs.

49
00:03:21,840 --> 00:03:25,440
The math ain’t mathing and\h
it actually never really did.

50
00:03:25,440 --> 00:03:29,840
Already in the 1970s governments began\h
to subsidize the pension funds with

51
00:03:29,840 --> 00:03:32,400
tax revenue – pushing the problem into the future.

52
00:03:32,400 --> 00:03:35,488
As has more or less every\h
single government since then.

53
00:03:35,488 --> 00:03:36,000
Well…

54
00:03:36,819 --> 00:03:38,456
The Future is Today

55
00:03:39,200 --> 00:03:44,720
In 2025, the German federal government spent\h
roughly a quarter of its annual tax revenues

56
00:03:44,720 --> 00:03:50,000
to fix holes in the pension system — on\h
top of the working population’s payments.

57
00:03:50,000 --> 00:03:56,160
Let’s say that again: One in four German\h
tax euros is used to pay out pensions today.

58
00:03:56,160 --> 00:04:01,680
More than on education, research,\h
infrastructure and defense combined!

59
00:04:01,680 --> 00:04:07,200
The wealth of the nation is redistributed from\h
the young and the working to the old and retired.

60
00:04:07,200 --> 00:04:11,120
And as the boomers retire\h
this will only get worse.

61
00:04:11,120 --> 00:04:15,840
It’s money that could be spent on things that help\h
the young and the working part of the population.

62
00:04:15,840 --> 00:04:19,680
Like incentives to start a family,\h
lower taxes, free childcare,

63
00:04:19,680 --> 00:04:24,640
cheap loans to buy homes, investments in\h
education, infrastructure or clean energy.

64
00:04:24,640 --> 00:04:27,360
There are so many things that\h
would help young Germans.

65
00:04:27,360 --> 00:04:31,680
But will Millennials and Gen-Z get\h
to enjoy similar pensions at least?

66
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:33,680
Well, it’s not very likely.

67
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:38,720
The current system only works for boomers because\h
their parents had more children and died younger,

68
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:42,800
and because Germany was booming\h
and the problem escalated slowly.

69
00:04:42,800 --> 00:04:45,280
Young people today don’t have all of that.

70
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:48,320
Ok that is depressing, but at\h
least the young can take care

71
00:04:48,320 --> 00:04:51,840
of their own retirement and save money, right?

72
00:04:51,840 --> 00:04:55,680
Well many sure would like to but\h
taxes and contributions are about

73
00:04:55,680 --> 00:05:01,040
40% of salaries for the average worker and\h
almost 50% in the highest tax brackets.

74
00:05:01,040 --> 00:05:02,880
One of the highest in the world.

75
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:07,280
Together with the rising cost of living and\h
sluggish wage growth, this makes it especially

76
00:05:07,280 --> 00:05:12,240
hard for young and middle aged Germans to\h
generate savings for their own retirements.

77
00:05:12,240 --> 00:05:13,680
One of the best investments,

78
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:18,240
wealth generators and places of comfort\h
and security is owning your own place.

79
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:21,200
But due to a mix of NIMBYS\h
preventing new development,

80
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:25,920
increasing mountains of new regulations making\h
building more expensive, and millions of people

81
00:05:25,920 --> 00:05:31,280
immigrating to Germany in the last few decades,\h
the housing supply is deeply behind demand.

82
00:05:31,280 --> 00:05:34,000
Renting and buying real\h
estate in metropolitan areas,

83
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:37,280
where young people actually want\h
to live, is so expensive today,

84
00:05:37,280 --> 00:05:42,400
that even couples with a dual income and good\h
jobs have a really hard time affording it.

85
00:05:42,400 --> 00:05:45,000
The generational contract in Germany is broken.

86
00:05:45,600 --> 00:05:48,864
And yet, some media voices continue to frame all

87
00:05:48,864 --> 00:05:52,160
this as a failure of young\h
people’s financial habits.

88
00:05:52,160 --> 00:05:57,360
The reality is complicated, and misleading\h
narratives permeate the media landscape.

89
