105
00:07:03,760 --> 00:07:05,838
And now back to the video.

106
00:07:06,720 --> 00:07:09,760
Young Germans are condemned to\h
pay off a huge loan on the future

107
00:07:09,760 --> 00:07:13,520
that the older generations have\h
generously granted themselves.

108
00:07:13,520 --> 00:07:15,600
And they don’t have the power to change this

109
00:07:15,600 --> 00:07:20,240
by voting – because German parties just\h
have no incentive to help young people.

110
00:07:20,240 --> 00:07:23,760
Demographic decline in a\h
democracy is a feedback loop:

111
00:07:23,760 --> 00:07:28,960
when seniors are the largest group of\h
voters, politicians make politics for them.

112
00:07:28,960 --> 00:07:33,680
This leaves young Germans facing a hard time\h
building wealth or getting their own homes,

113
00:07:33,680 --> 00:07:37,920
which makes them even less willing to start\h
families and have children, even if they want to.

114
00:07:37,920 --> 00:07:41,120
All of which is making the\h
demographic crash worse.

115
00:07:41,120 --> 00:07:45,520
Germany has become a society that works\h
for the old and relies on the young,

116
00:07:45,520 --> 00:07:49,280
making it really hard to create new young people.

117
00:07:49,280 --> 00:07:51,600
Baby boomers’ lives are affected, too.

118
00:07:51,600 --> 00:07:54,560
With unsustainable pension funds, inevitably,

119
00:07:54,560 --> 00:07:58,640
millions of older Germans will have\h
to work much longer than they thought.

120
00:07:58,640 --> 00:08:02,480
A retirement age of 70 or higher\h
is already being discussed.

121
00:08:02,480 --> 00:08:06,640
Today about 20% of German pensioners\h
live in poverty and that rate is all

122
00:08:06,640 --> 00:08:10,240
but guaranteed to increase\h
significantly in the 2030s.

123
00:08:10,240 --> 00:08:15,760
Still, seniors and boomers, in total, own\h
the vast majority of Germany's wealth.

124
00:08:15,760 --> 00:08:21,440
Germans are even arguing about to what extent the\h
costs of social systems have gotten out of hand.

125
00:08:21,440 --> 00:08:25,520
Even in a high tax country like Germany\h
there is plenty of wealth disparity and

126
00:08:25,520 --> 00:08:29,520
opportunities to tax the rich and take\h
pressure off workers – alltough of course

127
00:08:29,520 --> 00:08:33,520
the details are fiercely debated so\h
we’ll not get into this right now.

128
00:08:33,520 --> 00:08:37,120
But the scale of the gap between what\h
workers pay and what is needed to cover

129
00:08:37,120 --> 00:08:42,720
boomers’ pensions is so enormous that even\h
raising taxes would only buy a bit of time.

130
00:08:42,720 --> 00:08:46,560
And beyond pensions, the welfare\h
and healthcare systems Germans

131
00:08:46,560 --> 00:08:50,400
rely upon may become unaffordable in the 2030s.

132
00:08:50,400 --> 00:08:54,640
The vast majority of health care costs\h
occur during the last quarter of your life.

133
00:08:54,640 --> 00:08:58,720
So just as the healthcare workforce\h
is shrinking due to demographics,

134
00:08:58,720 --> 00:09:01,600
the numbers of patients will explode.

135
00:09:01,600 --> 00:09:06,640
The waiting time for a specialist doctor is\h
already months in the state health care system.

136
00:09:06,640 --> 00:09:09,120
Ok, but what about immigration?

137
00:09:09,120 --> 00:09:13,120
Whatever your opinion on immigration\h
is, pro or against, please put it in

138
00:09:13,120 --> 00:09:17,520
a box and ignore it for a moment, we only\h
want to look at it from one perspective:

139
00:09:17,520 --> 00:09:19,709
Can it solve the population crash?

140
00:09:20,480 --> 00:09:22,800
Let’s look at the population again.

141
00:09:22,800 --> 00:09:26,160
If a country's pyramid looks like\h
this and you want to stabilize it

142
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:28,960
at the bottom, immigration will not do that.

143
00:09:28,960 --> 00:09:32,320
For one, it doesn’t actually make\h
your country that much younger.

144
00:09:32,320 --> 00:09:36,400
In Germany the birthrate of most of its\h
immigrants isn’t higher than the locals’.

145
00:09:36,400 --> 00:09:38,880
And if new immigrants have more children,

146
00:09:38,880 --> 00:09:43,280
they tend to adjust to the rest of\h
the population within two generations.

147
00:09:43,280 --> 00:09:47,840
Sure, immigration over the last few decades\h
has delayed the coming crash and in the

148
00:09:47,840 --> 00:09:53,600
transition period we’ll run into serious worker\h
shortfalls, especially in health care and nursing.

149
00:09:53,600 --> 00:09:57,520
So zero immigration doesn’t seem wise or feasible.

150
00:09:57,520 --> 00:10:02,400
But there’s a problem: If birthrates stay\h
as low as they are or go down even more,

151
00:10:02,400 --> 00:10:05,600
then the German population\h
will continue to shrink.

152
00:10:05,600 --> 00:10:10,240
And to keep it stable it would constantly\h
need to be replenished by new immigrants.

153
00:10:10,240 --> 00:10:15,200
Until they age and themselves need new\h
immigrants, to pay for their retirement.

154
00:10:15,200 --> 00:10:19,440
No matter if you think this is a good idea\h
or not – it is not actually possible – birth

155
00:10:19,440 --> 00:10:22,880
rates are crashing everywhere –\h
eventually immigration around the

156
00:10:22,880 --> 00:10:27,200
world will slow down massively – the\h
world is running out of young people.

157
00:10:27,200 --> 00:10:32,800
So immigration can delay the issue a bit\h
and ease the consequences, but that is it.

158
00:10:33,360 --> 00:10:36,400
Germany either has to solve\h
its demographic crash – or

159
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:39,566
its welfare state and pension systems will break.

160
00:10:40,320 --> 00:10:45,310
Conclusion and Opinion Part\h
– So How Over is Germany?

161
00:10:45,920 --> 00:10:51,360
The demographic crisis is the greatest danger\h
to German living standards, and social cohesion.

162
00:10:51,360 --> 00:10:55,120
And the same crisis is unfolding\h
in all western countries.

163
00:10:55,120 --> 00:10:57,840
Things are about to escalate in Germany, Italy,

164
00:10:57,840 --> 00:11:04,880
France and Poland – but the same issues are also\h
on the horizon in the US, Argentina or Canada.

165
00:11:04,880 --> 00:11:07,280
The reality nobody wants to talk about is

166
00:11:07,280 --> 00:11:10,640
that solving the demographic\h
crisis will be very painful.

167
00:11:10,640 --> 00:11:13,440
It will require sacrifices from everyone and

168
00:11:13,440 --> 00:11:17,200
politicians seem incapable\h
of addressing it honestly.

169
00:11:17,200 --> 00:11:22,640
But to solve the demographic crisis for real,\h
something no nation has done successfully so far,

170
00:11:22,640 --> 00:11:27,040
might mean doing things that are\h
intensely unpopular with older voters.

171
00:11:27,040 --> 00:11:31,120
Instead of spending 25% of Germany’s\h
entire budget on the elderly,

172
00:11:31,120 --> 00:11:35,360
especially the wealthiest among them, we\h
could invest more of it in families — paying

173
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:40,000
for housing and childcare and making it\h
an amazing deal to have a big family.

174
00:11:40,000 --> 00:11:45,040
More than anything, our attitude to\h
kids and families needs to change.

175
00:11:45,040 --> 00:11:48,960
Demographics move slowly but then unstoppably.

176
00:11:48,960 --> 00:11:52,560
The next few decades will be\h
rough – but our societies can

177
00:11:52,560 --> 00:11:57,918
decide just how rough – and what kind of\h
societies will emerge on the other side.

